ober 1483":"12 October 1483","1414":"1414","1524":"1524","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1564":"1564","15 January 1524":"15 January 1524","about 1433":"about 1433","17 January 1466":"17 January 1466","about 1460":"about 1460","1438":"1438","Tilehurst, West Berkshire Unitary Authority, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England","Berkshire,,England,United Kingdom":"Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England":"Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Tilehurst Churchyard, Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bushnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Bushnells Green in Bucklebury (Berkshire), early recorded as <i>Bushenell</i> or <i>Busshendhill</i>.","History: Francis Bushnell came to New Haven, CT, in 1639, and was a founder of Guilford, CT."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":21,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bushnell was born in 1434, in Tilehurst, Berkshire, England, his father, Richard Bushnell, was 20 and his mother, Alice Maud Webb, was 20. He married Joan about 1460, in Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 January 1524, in Tilehurst, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 90, and was buried in Tilehurst, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1434–15 January 1524":"1434–15. jaanuar 1524","1434–1524":"1434–1524","1438–1524":"1438–1524","1466–1564":"1466–1564","1414–1483":"1414–1483","1414–1466":"1414–1466","1483":"1483","12 October 1483":"12. oktoober 1483","1414":"1414","1524":"1524","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1564":"1564","15 January 1524":"15. jaanuar 1524","about 1433":"umbes 1433","17 January 1466":"17. jaanuar 1466","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1438":"1438","Tilehurst, West Berkshire Unitary Authority, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England","Berkshire,,England,United Kingdom":"Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England":"Sulham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tilehurst Churchyard, Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1434–15 January 1524":"1434–15. tammikuuta 1524","1434–1524":"1434–1524","1438–1524":"1438–1524","1466–